     <article class="post audio" id="112157762837"> 
      <figure class="post-media"> 
       <iframe src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F193213103&amp;visual=true&amp;liking=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;auto_play=false&amp;show_comments=false&amp;continuous_play=false&amp;origin=tumblr" frameborder="0" allowtransparency="true" class="soundcloud_audio_player" width="500" height="500"></iframe> 
      </figure> 
      <div class="post-content"> 
       <p>Are certain life goals healthier to pursue than others? <br></p>
       <p>In a <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/16/money-power-mental-health_n_6297946.html?1418762970">recent study</a>, psychologist Sheri Johnson of <a class="tumblelog" href="http://tmblr.co/mnQIjaEIkwAf296zT1-hltQ">ucberkeley</a> found that people who pursued extrinsic life goals such as fame and wealth were at a much higher risk for mental health issues such as mania, psychopathy, depression and anxiety. Johnson explains that people generally strive for either extrinsic or intrinsic goals.<br></p> 
      </div> 
      <footer class="post-foot"> 
       <ul class="post-meta"> 
        <li><a href="http://ucsciencetoday.com/post/112157762837/are-certain-life-goals-healthier-to-pursue-than" title="Thursday, 26 February 2015 @ 15:21:11">26 Feb 2015 / 8 notes</a></li> 
        <li class="post-like-btn"><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/112157762837/toLhyOX6" class="reblog_button" style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;">
